 we went out there to be try and useful.  And then after that, I kept going back and working with other groups, with more long-term refugees, because the Hungarians were all swishing through on their way to Canada mostl
y, so they needed to learn English and they needed to have a bit of cultural encouragement.  But there were others who had been in these camps for years, actually, and had just kind of given up, even though nobody was nasty to them \endash  that\rquote 
s what was interesting \endash  nobody was stigmatising them, or cutting them out or anything.  Now they might, but at that time, the Austrians, particularly, were very generous, very accommodating.  So that was an interesting thing, that it\rquote 
s not always the bad guys who stop people integrating, they can do it themselves.
