\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11152896 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Sandra:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 Well, I\rquote ve always wanted to be useful, which has been, I think, a good thing, but sometimes it\rquote 
s resented, and funnily enough, it\rquote s much more fashionable now.  But in the past, I remember somebody saying to me \endash  I\rquote m sure it wasn\rquote t Firth \endash  but somebody saying to me, \'93You don\rquote 
t need to do applied stuff, because you\rquote re bright enough to do the real thing\'94. So it was very much a second class citizen thing.  But I just have that maybe a slightly practical be
nt, that I think that all the analytic cleverness that we might be able to claim, is no good if it doesn\rquote t say so}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11152896 mething about the real world.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 So that the original question, as I remember it now \endash  and it\rquote s an awfully long time ago \endash  was, \'93How come the colonial type money that is spent in Lesotho, just doesn\rquote 
t seem to do anything?  Doesn\rquote t seem to make any difference\'94.  That was the original idea, that okay, there wasn\rquote t an awful lot of it, but even that which was available, why isn\rquote t it making any differen
ce?  So you go and find out about communication, and about all that stuff, and the way people lived, and the way people saw it, and the usual anthro}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11152896 pological range of questions.  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 And, of course, it was an incredible experience.  I mean, that first fieldwor
k, especially in a place which is very different from where you normally live. In the books they say that this is an important aspect of becoming an anthropologist, that you have to be shocked down to your socks, you know!  And I certainly was!  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid94135 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Elaine:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
Can you tell me some of the experiences you had when you first arrived, for example?  
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11152896 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Sandra:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 Well, I mean, the physical environment wasn\rquote 
t very different.  But I was sort of allocated to live in the house of an Englishwoman who worked in the Colonial Office, whose name I\rquote ve forgotten altogether. And at that time \endash  don\rquote 
t forget, this is the sixties, this is a long time ago \endash  and almost everybody, was very much against, or very much doubting of the sense of going to live in a village, in a mud hut, with a 
whole load of Africans. So that I really had to make a big effort to get into the the Basuto circle.  And I remember learning, by some of these things you learn by accident, and I remember learning that, in a lot of African cultures, it\rquote 
s more of an honour to be visited than to be invited, so if you want to spend time with an African family, you invite yourself.  You arrive and you say, \'93I\rquote m visiting you\'94
, and they were very pleased about that.  And then eventually I got to go and found a village where I was acceptable. And the people in Maseru were very worried, you know, \'93You must keep up standards\'94, and \'93You mustn\rquote t go native\'94
, there was all a lot of anxiety about that, I was a young white woman of a good family, and why would you do that?  That\rquote s not sensible!  But I actually got q}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11152896 
uite sick with a gastro thing. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 This is really one of the moments - again, I think I\rquote 
ve written that up, but there are certain moments where you move in terms of the people that you\rquote re wanting to know, where you move from one category into another category, and they\rquote 
re quite distinct steps.  And the one that I remember particularly - don\rquote t forget this is South Africa, Southern African, in the sixties \endash  so to see a white woman trying to carry her own water and sweep her own house, 
that was almost funny.  But they still called me \'93Madam\'94 because I was a white woman.  And then there was an occasion when, during this illness, which, of course, I wasn\rquote t going to give up - you don\rquote 
t give up!  I mean, nobody gives up!  There was the opening of some agricultural project. Actually, I feel quite ill, just thinking about it now, so forgive me if I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11152896 
 suddenly rush from the room!  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 But we were sitting in the sun while everybody made speeches, and it was terribly terribly hot, and I was feeling terr
ibly sick, and I kept swigging this thing we all took when we had stomach stuff in the field, and I managed it while we were sitting outside, but then we went inside for the feast, and it was very crowded, and again, very hot, and there was a lot of sligh
tly greasy food, and everybody was celebrating and it was very convivial, but suddenly I knew that I\rquote 
d just lost it.  So I ran from this place to the edge of the village, which is where you go, in Lesotho, or where you used to go, if you had to defecate or be sick or anything like that - they had no latrines, but you\rquote 
d get out of the village.  So I got as far as the edge of the village, and I must have been massively sick, I must have passed out, actually, and I came to kind of lying in the lap of a wonderfu
l old crone who was mopping my brow with a grubby cloth, and clucking and saying, \'93It\rquote s all right\'94.  You know, \'93You\rquote re all right.  You\rquote re all right!\'94.  And from that moment, they\rquote 
d seen me vulnerable, and from that moment, they stopped calling me \'93Madam\'94, and they started calling me \'93Osi\'94, which is \'93big sister\'94.  So I had changed because I had got over that particular hurdle.  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid94135 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Elaine:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
So was that a plus, in terms of they were for you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Sandra:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
Oh, absolutely.  Absolutely.   Yeah.  And I think that you can\rquote 
t necessarily set that up.  I mean, you can do things like sweeping your own floor, but in that sort of setting, it was somewhat easier because the stereotype of white people was so strong that you could break it by doing something like that. Whereas when
 I worked in the Alps or in places where the cultural difference isn\rquote t so - not the cultural difference, but the social boundary, isn\rquote t so desperate, it\rquote 
s harder to break it. So I think that, going back to the business of your first fieldwork is supposed to be traumatic \endash  that\rquote s what the founding mothers and fathers said.
