\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Elaine:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
Well, you certainly had the experience!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Sandra:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
Yeah.  But what happens if you work in - I mean, I\rquote ve worked in my own society, and urban, and all of that, but not as my first project. And I\rquote 
ve often wondered, with students, whether they miss something by not having the culture shock.  A lot of people, now, they go home to their lovers every night.  It\rquote s like a 9-5 job.  And I don\rquote t know how you can get that sense of, \'93I
\rquote m out here by myself, and I need these people to make me human again\'94, which I think is part of the game, part of the job, actually.  I don\rquote t mean to say that it can\rquote t be done, but I think it must be different.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Elaine:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 And so that\rquote 
s how you got over that hurdle.  And so how did it feel for you after that \endash  you know, once you got to the stage of becoming a sister?  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Sandra:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 Oh, much better. I don
\rquote t believe it when people say \'93I became a member of the community\'94, I think that\rquote s a little bit pretentious.  But certain
ly people were easier with me, and I was easier with them.  Because in the beginning, the children used to come and look in to my hut, and giggle and point, and nudge each other and so on. And that\rquote 
s actually where I learnt, in order to have something}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11152896  to say to them, I had learnt Sesotho}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
, I thought, at SOAS, from a very nice man who spoke all those languages, but it was pretty useless because he\rquote d told me about noun classes and things like that, but not what you do when 14 children are giggling and pointing
!  So I suddenly had this idea.  I had my old typewriter, and I knew how to say, \'93What is your father\rquote s name?\'94 or \'93Who is your father?\'94
 and then I would type it all down, and they were thrilled because they were there and so I had this. I thought, \'93I\rquote ve got data here. This is kinship.  This is fantastic stuff\'94
.  And when I looked back at it, I realised that asking a question like, \'93Who is your father?\'94 you can get all kinds of different answers.  So a lot of people had given the District Chief, and some had given Paramount Chief, and some}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11152896  had given their actual fathers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 .  So this was my first experience of kinship analysis on the ground. 
