\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Sandra:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 Well, maybe that\rquote 
s what I do, but it\rquote s certainly not how I would - I don\rquote t like to be narrowly defined, as I told you before.  And Firth was very strong about that.  He said, \'93If we get to the point of saying that anybody\rquote 
s view is as good as anybody else\rquote s view, what argument do we have, as a profession?\'94  You have to take some kind of Popperian [view] in the sense that I would want to say, \'93This is what\rquote 
s interesting.  This is my hypothesis about it, and now let me see whether it holds up\'94 \endash  that was the importance of him, I think.  But certainly the first fieldwork, although every fieldwork has its excitement and its traumas... 
