What was it like?  Well, I think it takes time, takes extra time.  I think that with that interdisciplinary, or multidisciplinary stuff really, I think you have to be quite clear that you\rquote re all looking at the same thing.  So, for example, we
\rquote re all looking at that bottle of water in the middle of the table, we\rquote re not looking at each other\rquote s faces. Oh, it was a very good team, because I wanted to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6957381 emphasis}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6957381\charrsid8210080 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
, all the way through, that it was multi, and not interdisciplinary, that is to say everybody stuck to their own disciplines, or everybody emphasised their own disciplines.  I think t
here is, sometimes, a tendency, when you put a set of people together, who have different backgrounds, is that there\rquote 
s an effort to melt it all down to the same thing, melt it all down to find the common ground.  Yes, you need the common ground in terms of, \'93What do we want to know?\'94 and \'93What are we studying?\'94. But }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\ul\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080  think you shouldn\rquote 
t go for the common ground in terms of disciplinary perspectives, or models, or whatever it is.  So you need to allow everybody to do their own thing, but somehow get over th
e difficulty of communicating your own thing.  So it does take a lot of sitting around the table and trying not to say, \'93That\rquote s ridiculous!\'94
 to each other!  But I was lucky because I was the convenor of that group, so in a sense I could call the shots.  But because we were all of equal status, in a way, more or less, that I couldn\rquote 
t call the shots that clearly.  So it was a very good experience.  But there were quite a lot of stand offs, and quite a lot of conflicts along the way. 
