s that kind of accumulation of contextual detail which, I think, is the job of the anthropologist, actually.  But you decide what it is you want to know, and then you decide, \'93How is it knowable?\'94  And then, as far as I\rquote 
m concerned, you invent, on the hoof, ways of knowin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid132344 g what it is you want to know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 But you\rquote ve
 got to formulate your questions, I think \endash  at least in your own head.  There is a kind of division in anthropology between people who think you should not go in with any kind of a hypothesis, you shouldn\rquote t say, \'93Well, I suspect it
