The Turin thing was - I can\rquote t remember now the titles \endash 
 but it was migrants and hosts in the same market area in Turin, the old market area, which was about to be redeveloped, leading up to the Winter Olympics at the time, so they wanted to keep the exotic look of the area, but at the same time they needed to
 sanitise it, so they wanted migrants who were all upstanding citizens, and didn\rquote t traffic in drugs, and practice prostitution.  I was very lucky in that patch, actually, because I was attached to \endash 
 or I attached myself, through somebody that I met, and had become a friend as well as a colleague \endash 
 to a network dealing with the well-being of migrant sex workers across Europe, and so I learnt an awful lot about that, and about resilience, and about local options and so forth. One of the objectives of that particular network, called Tampep, actually 
\endash  T A M P E P \endash  was to make women, and sometimes men, but particularly women, aware of the options that they did have.  Some of them thought they weren\rquote t entitled to hospital treatment, for example, or they thought t
here was no way they could get out of the situation they were in. So I felt very sympathetic to this organisation, because their whole thing was, \'93Look, there are options out there that you could take up, and that we\rquote ll help you take up\'94
.  It was called something like, \'93Host Migrant Options in the Informal Economy\'94.  It had an economic bent on the livelihood side, so to speak.  \'93Informal economy\'94 is something which has always interested me a lot \endash 
 the unenumerated, invisible stuff, which is all about how people get by, of course \endash  because very few people are employed in the world, they have to do something else.
