t experience the other version, but it does seem, to me, to be an enormously important part of my life, as much now, or maybe even more now, than when they were small.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Elaine:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 Now, looking back o
n your working career, on your work, what have you been most proud of?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Sandra:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
Most proud of?  God!  I quite like a couple of books that I\rquote ve written.  But I think most proud of would be really in terms of inventing research strategies. The strategy of us
ing local residents to actually do the ethnographic work, training them to do it, paying them to do it, giving them a certificate to say they\rquote ve been trained, all of that.  I think planning it demonstrates what I believe about people \endash 
 that they have enormous capacity that nobody\rquote s ever looked at, many of them.  But also I think it improves the quality of the material.  So probably I\rquote m quite proud of that.  I don\rquote t know, pride is something that I\rquote 
m not very good at, to be frank.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Elaine:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
You mentioned you like some of the books you\rquote ve written.  Which ones are those, in particular?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Sandra:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 I like }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 Eight London Households}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 , and I quite like - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 Kampala Women}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080  was quite nice, it\rquote s a nice book I think.  And hopefully, this one \endash  the current one \endash  
is going to be a nice book.  It\rquote s funny when you look at stuff that you\rquote ve written, sometimes I have no recollection of myself writing it.  I think, \'93Oh, that\rquote s interesting!\'94  Or, \'93That\rquote s badly done\'94, or \'93
Oh, that\rquote s not bad\'94.  But I don\rquote t visualise myself sitting at a typewriter, or at a computer, writing that paragraph.  It\rquote s very strange how it flushes out.  I recognise the sentiment and the ideas, but I don\rquote 
t remember the production.  I think a lot of writers have that, once it\rquote s down on the page, it\rquote s gone, so to speak.  No, I was proud of the fact that Harry Smith, or whatever he was called - I should remember exactly - rang me up and said, 
\'93We did the survey together\'94. That\rquote s - I think that\rquote s good.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Elaine:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
 That was a good moment for you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Sandra:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
That was a very good moment, yeah.  I mean, I get very irritated when anthropologists say, \'93Oh, you become part of a community\'94, and \'93You make these wonderful lifetime friendships\'94. I think that that\rquote 
s bunkum, hokum, on the whole, because you are in a different - you do make, of course, very good friends, and some of them you keep for a lifetime, but I don\rquote t think you ever become an ordinary part of another community.  I\rquote 
m not even sure I\rquote m a part of my own community, let alone somebody else\rquote s!  But when you hear anthropologists saying that they were completely accepted, or they were completely absorbed - the point is that you don\rquote 
t have the same perspective on their ordinary life as they have.  You\rquote re looking at it; and you know it\rquote s going to end.  It\rquote s not - I mean, the ordinary life experienced over a 12 month period or a five year period, it\rquote 
s not the same as ordinary life for the rest of your life.  So I think there\rquote s a lot of pretension in the discipline which I could do without.  I mean, why should anybody care - but which I don\rquote 
t like, which embarrasses me, actually.  I think it can be an embarrassing little discipline, anthropology!  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Elaine:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 I\rquote 
ve never heard it quite put that way before! I\rquote ve heard of racism, it being described as a racist discipline, certainly in the beginning, but not...
\par  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6828992 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7229103 Sandra:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
