s much too simplistic.  I mean, racist in the sense that it recognises cultural, social, physical maybe, differences \endash  if that\rquote s what you\rquote re going to call racist.  I know that Michael Ban
ton distinguishes between racist and racialist, which is probably useful.  No, I think it\rquote s much too easy to label things racist.  But this is possibly my own life experience that comes in.  I guess you would understand.  But no, I thin}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6828992 k we can be very pretentious.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
I remember having this discussion when we were talking about trying to make anthropology more applicable, there was a time when we thought there were going to be no more academic jobs for anthropologists, so we had to somehow prepare our graduat
e students for the real world, and the thing was that if somebody asks you to do a piece of applied work, you have to recognise that they\rquote 
ve only got a certain amount of time and a certain amount of money, and they need a fairly straightforward response.  Now, if you say, \'93Oh, I don\rquote t know, it\rquote s all about context.  It\rquote 
s very complicated.  I need two or three years to work this out, then I can tell you\'94, and so on, and so on, that there is no reason why they should employ you. You know, \'93We have the secret, and you couldn\rquote t possibly understand it\'94
. I mean, in a way, it\rquote s all about commonsense, isn\rquote t it? It\rquote s all about, \'93Ah yes!  Now I remember!\'94  You know, all you\rquote re doing is, you\rquote re bringing the bits together, and you\rquote re saying, \'93
Look, we all know this.  You know this.  I know this, al}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6828992 l I\rquote ve done is formulate it\'94.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid94135\charrsid8210080 
I remember Paul Stirling, I think it was, saying that the anthropology profession was behind the group of us who were trying to make more jobs for anthropology graduates, and saying, \'93Okay.  Here we are.  Here we\rquote 
ve got X number of industries who are clamouring to have an anthropologist to solve their problems\'94.  And I, as the kind of broker, I look behind me, and there\rquote s nobody there.  So that there\rquote s a lot of talk about, \'93
Oh, we can do this.  We can solve problems.  We\rquote re so clever, we\rquote re this, that, and the other\'94 - and then when someone says, \'93Okay, tell me\'94, we shuffle our feet and go in the other direction, because we\rquote 
re so afraid.  Many people are very afraid of sticking their necks out, of actually saying, \'93Well, I think that if A then B\'94.  Of course they\rquote re not going to be right every time, but you\rquote 
ve got to give it a go, I think.  And so on one hand we\rquote re saying we can solve everything, on the other hand we\rquote re very afraid to take on issues.
